 © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Raines  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Raines","meanings":["English: variant of   Raine  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Rayne (Essex), recorded in the Domesday Book as <i>Raines</i> in the 11th century. The etymology of the placename is uncertain, but it may derive from Old English <i>hrægene</i> ‘hut, shelter’ or from a pre-English river name for Pods Brook (a river on which Rayne lies), cognate with the German river name Regen (a tributary of the Danube), formed from the Indo-European root <i>reg-</i> ‘wet, moisten, water’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Rennes in Brittany, France."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":44,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":117,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Thomas Reynes of Clifton Reynes was born about 1338, in Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England as the son of Sir Thomas Reynes of Clifton Reynes and Cecelia Tyringham. He married Lady Joan de Seyton in 1352. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in his hometown, and was buried in Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"about 1338–":"umbes 1338–Surnud","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1353–1383":"1353–1383","1355–1428":"1355–1428","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1300–1352":"1300–1352","–Female":"Surnud","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1353":"1353","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1353":"umbes 1353","1428":"1428","Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England","St Mary's Churchyard, Clifton Reynes, Milton Keynes Borough, Buckinghamshire, England":"Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1338–":"noin 1338–Kuollut","1338–Male":"1338–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1332–Female":"1332–Kuollut","1353–1383":"1353–1383","1355–1428":"1355–1428","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1300–1352":"1300–1352","–Female":"Kuollut","1352":"1352","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1338":"1338","about 1338":"noin 1338","1455":"1455","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1420":"1420","1332":"1332","1353":"1353","about 1355":"noin 1355","about 1353":"noin 1353","1428":"1428","Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Clifton Reynes, Buckinghamshire, England","St Mary's Churchyard, Clifton Reynes, Milton Keynes Borough, Buck